    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Unjust Sacrifice,'' by Robert A. Sirico (Op-Ed, Sept. 28):</p>
        <p>Father Sirico says it is never correct to sacrifice one life to save another. But in the case of the 8-week-old twins joined at the pelvis, if doctors choose not to sacrifice one child's life, they thereby make the choice to sacrifice both.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Unjust Sacrifice,'' by Robert A. Sirico (Op-Ed, Sept. 28):</p>
        <p>Father Sirico says it is never correct to sacrifice one life to save another. But in the case of the 8-week-old twins joined at the pelvis, if doctors choose not to sacrifice one child's life, they thereby make the choice to sacrifice both.</p>
        <p>For someone who wishes to choose life, the choice is clear: one choice leads to one saved life; the other choice leads to two lost lives.</p>
        <p>DONALD A. SMITH  East Setauket, N.Y., Sept. 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
